where they
put vice president-elect Mike
Pence in charge.

06:46.806 --> 06:51.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so this is something that
you also saw
during the campaign where Donald
Trump went

06:51.111 --> 06:53.446 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
through several different
campaign managers.

06:53.480 --> 06:56.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's now going through a few
different transition
heads.

06:56.816 --> 06:59.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, you're starting to see
sort of a pattern
emerge here.

06:59.219 --> 07:01.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In the grand
scheme of things,
does it matter?

07:01.154 --> 07:05.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I probably couldn't tell you who
managed the
transition for the last three,
four, ever

07:05.792 --> 07:06.760 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
presidents?

07:06.793 --> 07:07.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALEX ISENSTADT: Well, it's a
great question.

07:07.794 --> 07:09.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, to some extent, this is
inside baseball.

07:09.062 --> 07:11.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's parlor game stuff.

07:11.064 --> 07:14.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But to some degree, it does
indicate perhaps
something about Donald Trump's
leadership

07:14.834 --> 07:19.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
style, how he oversees things,
and exactly
how he's going to make some
decisions.

07:19.372 --> 07:23.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This comes at a time when a lot
of Americans
are looking for more information
on how Donald

07:23.410 --> 07:26.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump is going to lead and how
he makes key
decisions.

07:26.046 --> 07:27.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And there also
seems to
be this tension.

07:27.747 --> 07:31.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What he wanted on the campaign
was -- he ran
as an outsider.

07:31.151 --> 07:32.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He wanted people from outside
Washington.

07:32.886 --> 07:37.524 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Yet, right now, when you
actually have lots
and lots of jobs to fill, he's
calling on

07:37.557 --> 07:38.525 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
some insiders.

07:38.558 --> 07:40.360 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALEX ISENSTADT: Absolutely.

07:40.393 --> 07:43.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look at the names that you're
hearing talked
of for top jobs, people like
Rudy Giuliani,

07:43.963 --> 07:46.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people like Jeff Sessions, the
Alabama senator.

07:46.299 --> 07:51.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These people are -- to some
degree, they're
insiders, but they also share a
similar trait,

07:51.771 --> 07:56.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is that they were all
loyal to him during
the campaign, at a time, during
a campaign,

07:56.209 --> 08:00.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when a lot of Republicans sought
to distance
themselves from Donald Trump.

08:00.547 --> 08:05.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's priding loyalty and he's
looking to those
who were loyal to him during the
campaign,

08:05.385 --> 08:07.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who stood behind him.

08:07.187 --> 08:10.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: He's also now
getting the
intelligence briefings on a
daily basis that

08:10.223 --> 08:11.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
